<methodology slug="accessibility-first-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Design-phase methodology preventing 70-80% of WCAG 2.2 issues: contrast (4.5:1), touch targets (44x44px), focus visibility in tokens. Design-stage fixes cost 5-10x less than post-launch.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>wcag</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
      <tag>design-system</tag>
      <tag>tokens</tag>
      <tag>inclusive-design</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>accessibility</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Accessibility-First Design</title>

    <summary>A design-phase methodology that prevents 70-80% of WCAG 2.2 issues before engineering begins. Enforce contrast ratios (4.5:1 body, 3:1 large/UI), touch targets (44x44px), visible focus states, semantic HTML structure, and motion controls at the design token and component-spec level. Issues caught at design time cost 5-10x less than post-launch remediation.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Most accessibility defects are traceable to decisions made during design: color choices, layout spacing, animation defaults. Catching them at the Figma/handoff stage removes them from the code-review and QA cycle entirely. Embedding a11y constraints in design tokens and component approval criteria makes compliance structural rather than manual.</p>
      <p>Preventing a11y issues at design time is 5-10x cheaper than post-launch remediation. The cost escalates through the development lifecycle: design-stage fixes are CSS changes; code-stage fixes require refactoring; production fixes trigger legal and remediation obligations.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new product, design system, or major redesign.</item>
        <item>Establishing design-token contrast rules and focus-state baselines for a component library.</item>
        <item>Onboarding new designers — the checklist is the working agreement.</item>
        <item>Pre-handoff QA: validating Figma frames before engineering begins.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure code-fix sprints where designs are frozen — code-level a11y patterns (semantic HTML, ARIA, focus management) are the right tool.</item>
        <item>Marketing landing pages with one-off visual gimmicks — apply principles but don't gate launch on WCAG 2.2 AAA.</item>
        <item>When the design hasn't started — load design first; applying checklists too early constrains ideation.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="color-and-contrast">
      <p>Contrast rules enforced at the token level prevent brand colors from failing standards before any component is built.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enforce a minimum contrast ratio of 4.5:1 for body text and 3:1 for large text (18pt+), UI components, and focus indicators; embed these thresholds in design tokens so non-compliant primitives cannot be exported.</statement>
        <rationale>WCAG 2.2 SC 1.4.3 and 1.4.11 define these ratios. Encoding them in tokens prevents a designer from accidentally choosing a brand color that fails at the theme level before any component is built.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never use color as the sole indicator of meaning; pair every color signal with a shape, label, or pattern.</statement>
        <rationale>Approximately 8% of males have color vision deficiency. Color-only signals (red = error) are invisible to this population and fail WCAG SC 1.4.1.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Error state with multiple indicators">
        <note>Error state: red border + error icon + "Error:" label prefix. Three independent signals, any one sufficient.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Color-only error signal">
        <note>Error state: red border only. Color-blind users see no distinction from normal state.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="touch-targets-and-spacing">
      <p>Touch-target sizing and focus visibility rules prevent motor-impairment and keyboard-navigation failures.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set minimum interactive element size to 44x44 CSS pixels (or platform equivalent); ensure sufficient spacing between adjacent targets so misfire probability is low.</statement>
        <rationale>WCAG 2.2 SC 2.5.8 (Target Size, Minimum) formalizes this. Spacing matters independently of size — clustered 44px targets still cause misfires for users with motor impairments or tremor.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Make focus indicators visible with at least 3:1 contrast against the adjacent background; never rely on browser defaults which often fail this threshold.</statement>
        <rationale>WCAG 2.2 SC 2.4.11 (Focus Appearance, Minimum) requires a visible focus ring. Browser defaults (thin dotted outline) are often invisible on colored backgrounds.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="semantic-structure-and-motion">
      <p>Semantic and motion rules prevent screen-reader navigation failures and vestibular/cognitive barriers.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Specify heading level (H1-H6), landmark roles (nav, main, header, footer), and ARIA labels in design handoff annotations; do not leave semantic decisions to developer interpretation.</statement>
        <rationale>Developers recreate heading hierarchies inconsistently without explicit annotation. Screen reader users navigate by headings; a flat or misordered hierarchy breaks the primary navigation pattern.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Include pause/stop controls for all auto-playing animations longer than 5 seconds; respect prefers-reduced-motion at the CSS level.</statement>
        <rationale>WCAG 2.2 SC 2.2.2 (Pause, Stop, Hide) and 2.3.3 (Animation from Interactions) protect users with vestibular disorders and cognitive disabilities from motion that prevents reading or causes nausea.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow-and-gotchas">
      <p>Run a Figma-plugin-driven audit before handoff: subagent A pulls frames via Figma REST API, subagent B runs contrast/target/focus checks, subagent C generates a remediation list with specific frame IDs and proposed fixes. Loop with the designer; do not merge fixes blindly. Engineering handoff includes the audit report so developers know what has and has not been verified.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never apply automated contrast or target-size fixes without designer review; fixes often break visual hierarchy (e.g., darkening a brand color to pass AA).</statement>
        <rationale>Automated fixes optimize for the accessibility metric, not for design intent. A darkened brand primary may pass contrast but invalidate the brand. Fixes must be flagged for designer decision, not silently applied.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Frame audit prompt pattern">
        <note>Figma frame audit: "For each Figma frame, output JSON: { frame_id, issues: [{ rule, severity, element_id, current, required, fix_hint }] }. Rules: contrast (4.5:1 body, 3:1 large), target_size (&gt;=44x44), focus_visible, color_only, motion_pause, time_limit, semantic_handoff_present. Severity: blocker (WCAG 2.2 AA fail) | warn | info."</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinating WCAG criterion numbers (e.g., citing "WCAG 1.4.13" for an issue that is actually 1.4.11).</description>
        <reason>Agents are prone to criterion number errors. Constrain to a pre-validated rule list and require the agent to cite the exact SC number and name. Reviewers will catch and reject incorrect citations.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Estimating contrast ratios from screenshots rather than extracting hex values from tokens or the DOM.</description>
        <reason>Screenshot-based contrast estimation is unreliable due to JPEG compression, rendering engine differences, and anti-aliasing. Always extract actual color values programmatically.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Generating false positives for "color not the only indicator" on icons that already have adjacent labels.</description>
        <reason>Agents apply this rule mechanically without understanding that a color-coded icon with a text label already satisfies SC 1.4.1. Provide context including adjacent element content.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Track accessibility issues found at design stage versus handoff stage versus production; the ratio of design-stage finds to later-stage finds is the shift-left KPI.</statement>
        <rationale>If most finds are in production rather than design, the design-phase process is not working. The KPI makes the shift-left investment visible and improvable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Embed contrast and target-size constraints in design tokens; primitives that fail standards never get exported.</item>
        <item>Bake focus-visible styles into base components, not opt-in — designers forget, devs inherit the lapse.</item>
        <item>Pair the checklist with a Figma library: every interactive component has a focus state variant. No focus variant = component not approved.</item>
        <item>Track a11y issues found at design vs handoff vs production. The shift-left is your KPI.</item>
        <item>Annotate non-visible semantics in handoff (heading levels, ARIA roles, aria-label intent) — devs recreate it inconsistently otherwise.</item>
        <item>Real screen-reader and keyboard-only tester pass on critical flows before release. Tools cannot replace this human checkpoint.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>CLI tools for design-phase accessibility checking:</p>
      <list>
        <item>axe-core: Run a11y rules against rendered HTML. Install: npm i -D @axe-core/cli</item>
        <item>pa11y: URL-based a11y testing in CI. Install: npm i -g pa11y</item>
        <item>lighthouse: Includes a11y category, easy CI integration. Install: npm i -g lighthouse</item>
        <item>figma-rest-api clients: Pull frames/tokens for audit. https://www.figma.com/developers/api</item>
        <item>playwright + axe-playwright: E2E + a11y in same run. Install: npm i -D @axe-core/playwright</item>
        <item>wcag-color: Contrast math beyond simple ratios (APCA, WCAG 3). Install: npm i wcag-color</item>
        <item>tota11y: Visual a11y QA in browser (browser bookmarklet). https://khan.github.io/tota11y/</item>
      </list>

      <p>SaaS and plugin services:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Stark (Figma plugin): Strong contrast/color-blindness sim, focus-order check. Partial REST support.</item>
        <item>Able (Figma plugin): Lightweight contrast checks. Limited agent support.</item>
        <item>Deque axe DevTools: Most-used a11y CI tool. Agent-friendly CLI.</item>
        <item>Equal Access (IBM): Headless a11y scanner, OSS.</item>
        <item>Storybook a11y addon: Per-component runtime checks, OSS.</item>
        <item>EvinceQA: Continuous a11y monitoring, agent-friendly REST.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/a11y_quick.ts" purpose="Contrast ratio calculator, WCAG AA/AAA level checker, and touch-target size validator"/>
    </templates>

